This false value triggers two critical bugs: First, it leads to `vmpressure` reporting that no memory was reclaimed, even though MGLRU did all the work. Second, and this is the most dangerous, it prevents `kswapd` from clearing its "hopeless" state. So, `kswapd` might give up on an entire node because it thinks it's failed, even though we actually *did* reclaim memory via MGLRU. This would trigger an OOM. The patch actually CLAIMS to fix the OOM, but it causes the OPPOSITE!

This bad accounting leaks into other functions too. `shrink_lruvec` has a similar problem of double counting the reclaim targets: legacy is told to continue reclaiming even after the initial target has been met.

The other race I found is `lru_gen_change_state`. This is not a critical bug, because there is race-mitigation code: when enabled/disabled, the state is set, then legacy is cleaned up, and then the MGLRU code is enabled.

In short, there is critical logic errors in `shrink_node` that cause serious errors in `kswapd` and `vmpressure`.


